div.p:
So by the ſpirit of Love, he means the contrary frame, or habitual affection: For the ſpirit of power, and a ſound mind, are but coincident with Love, and make up that one frame of Spirit, oppoſed here to the ſpirit of Fear. Power is oppoſed to weakneſs, and a ſound mind (
                  〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉
               ) is oppoſed to ſtupidity, and abject thoughts; ſo that power, and a ſound mind, are but the immediate reſults of Love, as debility and ſtupidity are of Fear.
